# Chatvioso Component Standards

## Purpose

This document defines how **UI components must be designed and implemented** in Chatvioso.

It ensures:

- consistency
- reusability
- maintainability
- predictable UI behavior
- scalable architecture

All UI components must follow these rules.

---

# 1. Component Philosophy

Every component must follow these principles:

1. **Single Responsibility**
2. **Reusable**
3. **Composable**
4. **Predictable API**
5. **Consistent styling**
6. **Accessible by default**

Components must be built so they can be reused across multiple screens.

---

# 2. Component Categories

Components are divided into **three layers**.

## Layer 1 — UI Primitives

Location:

```
components/ui/
```

Examples:

- Button
- Input
- Textarea
- Avatar
- Badge
- Tabs
- Dialog
- Drawer
- Tooltip
- Dropdown
- Switch
- Checkbox
- Radio
- Skeleton
- Spinner
- Separator

Rules:

- purely visual
- reusable across all features
- no feature logic
- variant-based styling

---

## Layer 2 — Shared Components

Location:

```
components/shared/
```

Examples:

- AppLogo
- PageHeader
- SectionHeader
- EmptyState
- ErrorState
- UserPresenceIndicator
- UnreadBadge
- StatusPill
- BackButton
- SearchInput

Rules:

- built using UI primitives
- reusable across multiple features
- minimal business logic

---

## Layer 3 — Feature Components

Location:

```
features/*/components
```

Examples:

```
features/messages/components/MessageBubble
features/conversations/components/ConversationListItem
features/contacts/components/ContactCard
```

Rules:

- feature-specific
- may contain feature logic
- should still be composable

---

# 3. Component Naming Rules

## Component names

Use **PascalCase**.

Good examples:

```
MessageBubble
ConversationListItem
ChatSidebar
ContactCard
ProfileAvatarEditor
```

Bad examples:

```
box
tempComponent
NewSection
ItemCard2
```

---

## File naming

Files must match component names.

Example:

```
MessageBubble.tsx
ConversationListItem.tsx
ChatSidebar.tsx
```

---

# 4. Component File Structure

Each component should follow a clean structure.

Example:

```
MessageBubble/
MessageBubble.tsx
MessageBubble.types.ts
MessageBubble.styles.ts (optional)
index.ts
```

Or a simpler version:

```
MessageBubble.tsx
```

depending on complexity.

---

# 5. Component API Design

Component props must be **clear and predictable**.

## Good API design

Example:

```
<Button
  variant="primary"
  size="md"
  loading
>
  Send
</Button>
```

Avoid APIs like:

```
<Button blue big rounded>
```

Use explicit props.

---

# 6. Button Standards

Buttons must use the shared **Button component**.

Variants:

- primary
- secondary
- outline
- ghost
- destructive
- link

Sizes:

- sm
- md
- lg

Example:

```
<Button variant="primary" size="md">
  Send Message
</Button>
```

---

## Button rules

Buttons must support:

- disabled state
- loading state
- icon support
- icon-only version
- keyboard focus state

---

# 7. Input Standards

All form inputs must use shared components.

Examples:

```
<Input />
<Textarea />
<Select />
<Checkbox />
<Switch />
```

---

## Input rules

Inputs must support:

- label
- placeholder
- validation
- error state
- disabled state
- helper text

Example:

```
<Input
  label="Email"
  placeholder="name@example.com"
  error="Invalid email"
/>
```

---

# 8. Avatar Component

Avatar component should support:

```
<Avatar
  src="..."
  name="Ali Haider"
  size="md"
/>
```

Features:

- fallback initials
- image loading
- size variants
- status indicator (optional)

Sizes:

- xs
- sm
- md
- lg
- xl

---

# 9. Badge Component

Badges are used for:

- unread count
- status
- labels
- tags

Example:

```
<Badge variant="primary">
  3
</Badge>
```

Variants:

- default
- primary
- success
- warning
- danger

---

# 10. Sidebar Navigation Item

Sidebar items must be consistent.

Structure:

```
SidebarItem
  icon
  label
  active state
  optional badge
```

Example:

```
<SidebarItem
  icon={ChatIcon}
  label="Chats"
  active
/>
```

---

# 11. Conversation List Item

Conversation items must display:

- avatar
- name
- message preview
- timestamp
- unread badge
- active state

Example layout:

```
[Avatar]  John Doe
          Last message preview
          12:45 PM      [2]
```

Rules:

- truncate long previews
- clear unread state
- active conversation highlighted

---

# 12. Message Bubble Component

Message bubbles must clearly distinguish:

- own message
- other message

Example API:

```
<MessageBubble
  text="Hello"
  time="12:32"
  isOwn
/>
```

---

## Message bubble rules

Must support:

- grouped messages
- attachments
- timestamps
- status indicators
- multiline text

---

# 13. Message Group Component

Messages from the same sender should group.

Example:

```
<MessageGroup
  sender="Ali"
  messages={[...]}
>
```

Rules:

- reduce avatar repetition
- consistent spacing
- maintain readability

---

# 14. Message Composer Component

Composer must support:

- multiline input
- send button
- attachment trigger
- disabled state
- keyboard send

Example:

```
<MessageComposer
  value={message}
  onSend={handleSend}
/>
```

---

# 15. Dialog / Modal Standards

Dialogs must use shared **Dialog component**.

Example:

```
<Dialog
  title="Create Group"
  open={isOpen}
  onClose={close}
>
  content
</Dialog>
```

Rules:

- consistent padding
- clear title
- close button
- escape key support

---

# 16. Drawer / Panel Standards

Drawers are used for:

- mobile panels
- details sidebar
- settings overlays

Example:

```
<Drawer
  open={isOpen}
  onClose={close}
  side="right"
>
```

---

# 17. Empty State Component

All empty states must use shared component.

Example:

```
<EmptyState
  title="No messages yet"
  description="Start the conversation."
/>
```

---

# 18. Loading Skeletons

Skeletons must match the shape of real UI.

Example:

```
<ConversationListSkeleton />
<MessageListSkeleton />
```

Rules:

- avoid layout jumps
- subtle animation

---

# 19. Accessibility Rules

All components must support:

- keyboard navigation
- focus states
- ARIA labels when necessary
- screen reader friendly labels

Example:

```
<Button aria-label="Send message">
```

---

# 20. Component Size Consistency

Avoid random sizing.

Examples:

```
Button heights
Input heights
Avatar sizes
Icon sizes
```

must be standardized.

---

# 21. Props Best Practices

Props should:

- be explicit
- avoid too many booleans
- use enums when needed

Good:

```
variant="primary"
size="md"
```

Bad:

```
big
blue
rounded
```

---

# 22. Composition Over Duplication

Prefer:

```
<Card>
  <CardHeader />
  <CardContent />
</Card>
```

instead of repeating layout code.

---

# 23. State Handling

Components should avoid managing unnecessary global state.

Prefer:

- local state
- controlled props
- hooks

---

# 24. Component Testing

Every critical UI component should be testable.

Examples:

- Button click
- Input validation
- Dialog open/close
- Message send

---

# 25. Definition of Done

A component is complete only if:

- reusable
- accessible
- styled using design tokens
- responsive
- predictable API
- documented with clear props
- no duplicated styling logic

---

# 26. Anti Patterns

Do not:

- create huge components
- mix layout + business logic
- hardcode styling
- use inline random styles
- duplicate UI code
- create similar components repeatedly

---

# 27. Final Goal

The component system should allow developers to build new screens **quickly and consistently** without reinventing UI patterns.
